<paper id="1967165764"><title>Combining knowledge sources to reorder N-best speech hypothesis lists</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="SRI International, Cambridge, UK" id="2110163086">Manny Rayner</author><author org="SRI International, Cambridge, UK" id="2987965630">David Carter</author><author org="Sri-international (Menlo Park, CA)" id="335441398">Vassilios Digalakis</author><author org="Sri-international (Menlo Park, CA)" id="2102238887">Patti Price</author></authors><n_citation>74</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>125108960</reference><reference>1509045587</reference><reference>1549964779</reference><reference>1990387894</reference><reference>2019627457</reference><reference>2046440743</reference><reference>2126597185</reference><reference>2139884663</reference><reference>2143990197</reference></references><venue id="2532822031" type="C">Human Language Technology</venue><doi>10.3115/1075812.1075858</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.44871">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47542">Speech recognition</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.4786">Natural language processing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Association for Computational Linguistics</publisher><abstract>A simple and general method is described that can combine different knowledge sources to reorder N-best lists of hypotheses produced by a speech recognizer. The method is automatically trainable, acquiring information from both positive and negative examples. In experiments, the method was tested on a 1000-utterance sample of unseen ATIS data.</abstract></paper>